 Internal Working of HashMap
 ==================================================================================
 -> Its an interface and its implementation are : 
     - HashMap : do not maintain the order.
     - HashTable : Synchronized version of HashMap.
     - LinkedHashMap : Maintain the insertion order.
     - TreeMap : sorts the data internally.
 -> Object that maps key to value.
 -> Can not contain duplicate key.
 -> A HashMap stores data in key–value pairs.
    
     HashMap<Key, Value>
                map.put("A", 10);
                map.put("B", 20);
                map.put("C", 30);
     It Internally create Array of Bucket. (Default size is 16)
               Array of Nodes (Buckets)
     map.put("A", 10);
        Step 1: Calculate HashCode
                hash = key.hashCode()  -- "A".hashCode() = 65         
        Step 2: Find Bucket Index
                index = hash % array_size  -- 65 % 16 = 1
        Step 3: Store Node      -- Bucket[1] → (A,10)
                Node {
                  int hash; -- 65
                  Key key;  -- A
                  Value value; -- 10
                  Node next; -- null
               }
               
   What if Collision Happens?
   Collision = two keys map to the same bucket. 
       "A".hashCode() % 16 = 1
       "Q".hashCode() % 16 = 1
     Both go to bucket 1.
     
   Before Java 8
   Collision handled using Linked List.
          Bucket[1]
             ↓
           (A,10) → (Q,40) → null
   After Java 8
      If bucket size > 8:
      Linked list converts into Red-Black Tree
      Improves performance
      
            Bucket[1]
        (Tree structure)
            (A,10)
            /    \
         (B,20)  (Q,40)
            
   Visual Diagram of HashMap
   --------------------------------
